373
00:15:55.400 --> 00:15:57.630
I come to observe;

374
00:15:57.630 --> 00:15:59.030
I give thee warning on it.

375
00:15:59.030 --> 00:16:00.630
I take no heed of thee;

376
00:16:00.630 --> 00:16:02.730
Thou art an Athenian,therefore welcome:

377
00:16:02.730 --> 00:16:04.230
I myself would have nopower;

378
00:16:04.230 --> 00:16:05.870
prithee, let my meat makethee silent.

379
00:16:05.870 --> 00:16:07.230
I scorn thy meat;

380
00:16:07.230 --> 00:16:10.330
'twould choke me, for Ishould ne'er flatter thee.

381
00:16:10.330 --> 00:16:14.300
O you gods, what a numberof men eats Timon,

382
00:16:14.300 --> 00:16:16.400
and he sees 'em not!

383
00:16:18.470 --> 00:16:20.170
It grieves me to see somany

384
00:16:20.170 --> 00:16:22.400
dip their meat in oneman's blood;

385
00:16:22.400 --> 00:16:26.030
and all the madness is, hecheers them up too.

386
00:16:26.030 --> 00:16:28.800
I wonder men dare trustthemselves with men:

387
00:16:28.800 --> 00:16:31.730
Methinks they should invitethem without knives;

388
00:16:31.730 --> 00:16:35.100
good for their meat, andsafer for their lives.

389
00:16:35.100 --> 00:16:37.330
There's much example forit;

390
00:16:37.330 --> 00:16:40.770
the fellow that sits next him,now parts bread with him,

391
00:16:40.770 --> 00:16:43.700
pledges the breath of himin a divided draught,

392
00:16:43.700 --> 00:16:45.400
is the readiest man tokill him.

393
00:16:45.400 --> 00:16:47.900
It has been proved.

394
00:16:47.900 --> 00:16:52.070
If I were a huge man, Iwould fear to drink at meals

395
00:16:52.070 --> 00:16:55.670
lest they should spy mywindpipe's dangerous notes:

396
00:16:55.670 --> 00:16:59.300
Great men should drink withharness on their throats.

397
00:17:02.200 --> 00:17:05.470
My lords, in heart.

398
00:17:08.730 --> 00:17:10.300
And let the health goround.

399
00:17:10.300 --> 00:17:12.570
Let it flow this way, mygood lord.

400
00:17:12.570 --> 00:17:13.570
Flow this way!

401
00:17:13.570 --> 00:17:14.570
A brave fellow!

402
00:17:14.570 --> 00:17:16.300
He keeps his tides well.

403
00:17:16.300 --> 00:17:20.500
Those healths will makethee and thy state lookill, Timon.

404
00:17:20.500 --> 00:17:23.000
Here's that which is tooweak to be a sinner,

405
00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:24.570
honest water,

406
00:17:24.570 --> 00:17:26.900
which ne'er left man inthe mire:

407
00:17:26.900 --> 00:17:29.530
It and my food are equals;

408
00:17:29.530 --> 00:17:32.370
there's no odds.

409
00:17:32.370 --> 00:17:36.430
Feasts are too proud togive thanks to the gods.

410
00:17:36.430 --> 00:17:39.830
Immortal gods, I craveno pelf;

411
00:17:39.830 --> 00:17:42.830
I pray for no man butmyself.

412
00:17:42.830 --> 00:17:45.000
Grant I may never prove sofond

413
00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:48.000
to trust man on his oathor bond;

414
00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.570
or a harlot, for herweeping;

415
00:17:50.570 --> 00:17:52.300
or a dog, that seemsa-sleeping;

416
00:17:52.300 --> 00:17:55.030
or a keeper with myfreedom;

417
00:17:55.030 --> 00:17:58.970
or my friends, if I shouldneed 'em.

418
00:17:58.970 --> 00:18:01.670
Amen.

419
00:18:01.670 --> 00:18:04.200
So fall to it.

420
00:18:04.200 --> 00:18:08.600
Rich men sin, and I eatroot.

421
00:18:08.600 --> 00:18:11.470
Much good dich thy goodheart, Apemantus.

422
00:19:12.230 --> 00:19:14.030
All!

423
00:20:41.200 --> 00:20:43.430
May it please Your Honor.

424
00:20:43.430 --> 00:20:46.470
Lord Lucius, out of hisfree love,

425
00:20:46.470 --> 00:20:49.230
hath presented to you fourmilk-white horses

426
00:20:49.230 --> 00:20:50.500
trapped in silver.

427
00:20:52.870 --> 00:20:54.670
I shall accept themfairly.

428
00:20:54.670 --> 00:20:57.970
Let the presents beworthily entertained.

429
