435
00:21:14.430 --> 00:21:17.230
Captain Alcibiades, yourheart's in the field now.

436
00:21:17.230 --> 00:21:19.570
My heart's ever at yourservice, my good lord.

437
00:21:19.570 --> 00:21:21.170
Had you rather be at abreakfast of enemies

438
00:21:21.170 --> 00:21:23.030
than a dinner of friends?

439
00:21:23.030 --> 00:21:25.000
So they were bleeding-new,my lord,

440
00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:27.130
there's no meat like them:

441
00:21:27.130 --> 00:21:29.730
I could wish my bestfriend at such a feast.

442
00:21:29.730 --> 00:21:32.370
Would all those flattererswere thy enemies then,

443
00:21:32.370 --> 00:21:34.770
that then thou mightst kill'em and bid me to 'em!

444
00:21:38.970 --> 00:21:41.770
Might we but have thathappiness, my lord,

445
00:21:41.770 --> 00:21:44.430
that you would once useour hearts,

446
00:21:44.430 --> 00:21:48.930
whereby we might expresssome part of our zeals,

447
00:21:48.930 --> 00:21:52.970
we should think ourselvesforever perfect.

448
00:21:52.970 --> 00:21:56.070
No doubt, my good friends,but the gods themselves

449
00:21:56.070 --> 00:21:58.670
have provided I shall havemuch help from you.

450
00:21:58.670 --> 00:22:01.630
How had you been myfriends else?

451
00:22:01.630 --> 00:22:04.870
