00:28:28.630 --> 00:28:29.930
well, in faith I should

530
00:28:29.930 --> 00:28:31.430
when all's spent,

531
00:28:31.430 --> 00:28:32.570
he would be crossed then,he could.

532
00:28:32.570 --> 00:28:34.670
'Tis pity bounty had noteyes behind,

533
00:28:34.670 --> 00:28:36.730
that man might ne'er bewretched for his mind.

534
00:28:45.570 --> 00:28:46.870
Ah, Flavius.

535
00:28:59.600 --> 00:29:03.170
My lord, honor me so muchas to advance this jewel;

536
00:29:03.170 --> 00:29:06.430
accept it and wear it,kind my lord.

537
00:29:06.430 --> 00:29:08.600
I am so far already inyour gifts

538
00:29:08.600 --> 00:29:09.930
So are we all.

539
00:29:12.070 --> 00:29:14.330
I beseech Your Honor,vouchsafe me a word;

540
00:29:14.330 --> 00:29:15.500
it does concern you near.

541
00:29:15.500 --> 00:29:16.630
Near!

542
00:29:16.630 --> 00:29:17.830
Why, then, another timeI'll hear:

543
00:29:20.130 --> 00:29:21.730
What will this come to?

544
00:29:21.730 --> 00:29:23.330
He commands us to provideand give great gifts,

545
00:29:23.330 --> 00:29:25.230
and all out of an emptycoffer:

546
00:29:25.230 --> 00:29:26.830
Nor will he know hispurse, or yield me this,

547
00:29:26.830 --> 00:29:28.630
to show him what a beggarhis heart is,

548
00:29:28.630 --> 00:29:30.870
being of no power to makehis wishes good.

549
00:29:30.870 --> 00:29:32.730
His promises fly so beyondhis state

550
00:29:32.730 --> 00:29:34.330
that what he speaks is allin debt;

551
00:29:34.330 --> 00:29:36.030
he owes for every word.

552
00:29:36.030 --> 00:29:37.900
He is so kind that he nowpays interest for it;

553
00:29:37.900 --> 00:29:39.700
his land's put to theirbooks.

554
00:29:39.700 --> 00:29:41.570
Well, would I were gentlyput out of office

555
00:29:41.570 --> 00:29:43.300
before I were forced out.

556
00:29:43.300 --> 00:29:45.200
Happier is he that has nofriend to feed

557
00:29:45.200 --> 00:29:47.400
than such that do evenenemies exceed.

558
00:29:47.400 --> 00:29:49.270
I bleed inwardly for mylord.

559
00:29:53.300 --> 00:29:55.170
You do yourselves too muchwrong,

560
00:29:55.170 --> 00:29:57.230
you bate too much of yourown merits:

561
00:29:57.230 --> 00:30:00.930
Here, my lord, a token ofour love.

562
00:30:00.930 --> 00:30:03.130
With more than commonthanks I will receive it.

563
00:30:03.130 --> 00:30:05.870
O, he is the very soul ofbounty!

564
00:30:05.870 --> 00:30:07.370
Now I do remember, mylord,

565
00:30:07.370 --> 00:30:08.830
you gave good words theother day

566
00:30:08.830 --> 00:30:10.500
of a bay courser I rodeon:

567
00:30:10.500 --> 00:30:12.270
it is yours, because youliked it.

568
00:30:12.270 --> 00:30:14.870
Oh, I beseech you, pardonme, my lord, in that.

569
00:30:14.870 --> 00:30:16.170
You may take my word.

570
00:30:16.170 --> 00:30:19.600
I know no man can justly praisebut what he does affect:

571
00:30:19.600 --> 00:30:21.600
I weigh my friend'saffection with mine own;

572
00:30:21.600 --> 00:30:22.600
I'll tell you true.

573
00:30:22.600 --> 00:30:23.600
I'll call to you.

574
00:30:23.600 --> 00:30:25.700
Oh, none so welcome.

575
00:30:25.700 --> 00:30:28.830
I take all and yourseveral visitations sokind to heart,

576
00:30:28.830 --> 00:30:30.470
'tis not enough to give;

577
00:30:30.470 --> 00:30:33.230
methinks I could dealkingdoms to my friends

578
00:30:33.230 --> 00:30:35.530
and ne'er be weary.

579
00:30:35.530 --> 00:30:39.430
Alcibiades, thou art a soldier,therefore seldom rich;

580
00:30:39.430 --> 00:30:42.770
It comes in charity tothee:

581
00:30:42.770 --> 00:30:44.830
for all thy living isamongst the dead.

582
00:30:44.830 --> 00:30:47.670
All the lands thou hastlie in a pitched field.

583
00:30:47.670 --> 00:30:50.570
Ay, defiled land, my lord.

584
00:30:50.570 --> 00:30:52.500
We are so virtuouslybound.

585
00:30:52.500 --> 00:30:53.570
And I to you.

586
00:30:53.570 --> 00:30:56.430
So infinitely endeared

587
00:30:56.430 --> 00:30:58.230
So I to you.

588
00:30:58.230 --> 00:31:00.100
Lights, more lights!

589
00:31:00.100 --> 00:31:03.130
The best of happiness,honor and fortunes,

590
00:31:03.130 --> 00:31:04.370
keep with you, Lord Timon!

591
00:31:04.370 --> 00:31:09.300
Ready for his friends.

592
00:31:09.300 --> 00:31:10.230
What a coil's here.

593
00:31:10.230 --> 00:31:12.730
Serving of becks andjutting-out of bums.

594
00:31:12.730 --> 00:31:14.430
I doubt whether their legsbe worth the sums

595
00:31:14.430 --> 00:31:15.870
that are paid for them.

596
00:31:15.870 --> 00:31:18.000
Friendship's full ofdregs.

597
00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:21.800
Methinks false hearts shouldnever have sound legs,

598
00:31:21.800 --> 00:31:25.430
thus honest fools lay outtheir wealth on curtsies.

599
00:31:28.800 --> 00:31:33.600
Now, Apemantus, if thouwert not sullen,

600
00:31:33.600 --> 00:31:34.930
I would be good to thee.

601
00:31:34.930 --> 00:31:37.070
No, I'll nothing:

602
00:31:37.070 --> 00:31:38.730
for if I should be bribedtoo,

603
00:31:38.730 --> 00:31:40.700
there would be none leftto rail upon thee,

604
00:31:40.700 --> 00:31:43.070
and then thou wouldst sinthe faster.

605
00:31:43.070 --> 00:31:44.470
Thou givest so long,Timon,

606
00:31:44.470 --> 00:31:48.400
I fear me thou wilt giveaway thyself in papershortly:

607
00:31:48.400 --> 00:31:51.330
what need these feasts,pomps and vainglories?

608
00:31:51.330 --> 00:31:54.430
Nay, and you begin to railupon society once,

609
00:31:54.430 --> 00:31:56.130
I am sworn not to giveregard to you.

610
00:31:56.130 --> 00:31:57.130
Farewell.

611
00:31:57.130 --> 00:31:58.300
Come again with better music.

612
00:31:59.530 --> 00:32:00.700
So thou wilt not hear me now;

613
00:32:00.700 --> 00:32:01.900
thou shalt not then:

614
00:32:01.900 --> 00:32:04.300
I'll lock thy heaven fromthee.

615
00:32:04.300 --> 00:32:09.270
Oh, that men's ears shouldbe to counsel deaf,

616
00:32:09.270 --> 00:32:10.830
but not to flattery.

617
00:32:18.300 --> 00:32:20.070
Here, my lord.

618
00:32:42.500 --> 00:32:43.530
Haste you to Lord Timon;

619
00:32:43.530 --> 00:32:44.770
Importune him for mymoneys;

620
00:32:44.770 --> 00:32:46.000
be not ceased by slightdenial,

621
00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:47.030
nor then silenced when

622
00:32:47.030 --> 00:32:48.700
"Commend me to yourmaster,"

623
00:32:48.700 --> 00:32:51.130
and the cap plays in theright hand, thus.

624
00:32:51.130 --> 00:32:53.900
But tell him, my uses cryto me,

625
00:32:53.900 --> 00:32:56.730
I must serve my turn outof mine own.

626
00:32:56.730 --> 00:32:58.270
His days and times arepast

627
00:32:58.270 --> 00:32:59.970
and my reliance on hisfracted dates

628
00:32:59.970 --> 00:33:01.700
have smit my credit:

629
00:33:01.700 --> 00:33:02.970
I love and honor him,

630
00:33:02.970 --> 00:33:05.700
but I must not break myback to heal his finger.

631
00:33:05.700 --> 00:33:07.000
Immediate are my needs,

632
00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:09.070
and my relief must not betossed and turned to mein words,

633
00:33:09.070 --> 00:33:11.900
but find supply immediate.

634
00:33:11.900 --> 00:33:13.500
Get you gone.

635
00:33:13.500 --> 00:33:15.500
Put on a most importunateaspect,

636
00:33:15.500 --> 00:33:18.670
a visage of demand, for, Ido fear,

637
00:33:18.670 --> 00:33:20.730
when every feather sticksin his own wing,

638
00:33:20.730 --> 00:33:22.630
Lord Timon will be left anaked gull,

639
00:33:22.630 --> 00:33:24.730
which flashes now aphoenix.

640
00:33:24.730 --> 00:33:25.730
Get you gone.

641
00:33:25.730 --> 00:33:26.730
I go, sir.

642
00:33:26.730 --> 00:33:27.870
Take the bonds along withyou,

643
00:33:27.870 --> 00:33:28.870
I will, sir.

644
00:33:28.870 --> 00:33:30.230
Have the dates incontempt.

645
00:33:30.230 --> 00:33:31.970
Go.

646
00:33:34.030 --> 00:33:36.000
No care, no stop!

647
00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:37.130
So senseless of expense,

648
00:33:37.130 --> 00:33:39.900
that he will neither knowhow to maintain it,

649
00:33:39.900 --> 00:33:41.530
nor cease his flow ofriot.

650
00:33:41.530 --> 00:33:44.200
Takes no account howthings go from him,

651
00:33:44.200 --> 00:33:46.530
nor resumes no care ofwhat is to continue.

652
00:33:46.530 --> 00:33:50.100
Never mind was to be sounwise, to be so kind.

653
00:33:50.100 --> 00:33:52.430
Oh, what shall be done?

654
00:33:52.430 --> 00:33:54.730
He will not hear, tillfeel.

655
00:33:54.730 --> 00:33:57.500
I must be round with him,now he comes from hunting.

656
00:33:57.500 --> 00:33:58.670
Fie, fie, fie!

657
00:33:58.670 --> 00:33:59.730
Good even.

658
00:33:59.730 --> 00:34:00.800
What, you come for money?

659
00:34:00.800 --> 00:34:02.430
Is it your business too?

660
00:34:02.430 --> 00:34:03.600
'Tis, and yours?

661
00:34:03.600 --> 00:34:04.600
Would we were alldischarged!

662
00:34:04.600 --> 00:34:05.600
I fear it.

663
00:34:05.600 --> 00:34:06.900
Here comes the lord.

664
00:34:06.900 --> 00:34:08.500
So soon as dinner's done,

665
00:34:08.500 --> 00:34:10.800
we'll forth again, myAlcibiades.

666
00:34:10.800 --> 00:34:11.800
With me?

667
00:34:11.800 --> 00:34:12.970
What is your will?

668
00:34:12.970 --> 00:34:15.670
My lord, here is a note ofcertain dues.

669
00:34:15.670 --> 00:34:17.900
Dues?

670
00:34:17.900 --> 00:34:19.100
Whence are you?

671
00:34:19.100 --> 00:34:20.330
Of Athens here, my lord.

672
00:34:20.330 --> 00:34:21.500
Go to my steward.

673
00:34:21.500 --> 00:34:22.600
Please it, Your Lordship,

674
00:34:22.600 --> 00:34:23.830
he has put me out to thesuccession

675
00:34:23.830 --> 00:34:25.330
of new days this month.

676
00:34:25.330 --> 00:34:26.570
My master is awaked togreat occasion

677
00:34:26.570 --> 00:34:27.930
to call upon his own,

678
00:34:27.930 --> 00:34:30.030
and humbly prays you that,with your other noble parts,

679
00:34:30.030 --> 00:34:31.770
you'll suit in giving himhis right.

680
00:34:31.770 --> 00:34:34.170
Mine honest friend, Iprithee, but repair to menext morning.

681
00:34:34.170 --> 00:34:35.170
Nay, good my lord!

682
00:34:35.170 --> 00:34:36.630
Contain thyself, goodfriend.

683
00:34:36.630 --> 00:34:37.630
One Varro's servant, mygood

684
00:34:37.630 --> 00:34:38.630
From Isidore;

685
00:34:38.630 --> 00:34:40.070
he humbly prays yourspeedy payment.

686
00:34:40.070 --> 00:34:41.530
If you did know, my lord,my master's wants

687
00:34:41.530 --> 00:34:43.070
'Twas due on forfeiture, mylord, six weeks and past.

688
00:34:43.070 --> 00:34:45.370
Give me breath!

689
00:34:45.370 --> 00:34:48.870
My lords, I beseech you,keep on;

690
00:34:48.870 --> 00:34:50.430
I'll wait upon youinstantly.

691
00:34:53.570 --> 00:34:57.570
Come hither, I pray you.

692
00:34:57.570 --> 00:34:59.800
I beseech you, how goesthe world

693
00:34:59.800 --> 00:35:01.930
that I am thus encounteredwith clamorous demands

694
00:35:01.930 --> 00:35:04.000
of debt, broken bonds,

695
00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:07.170
and the detention oflong-since-due debtsagainst my honor?

696
00:35:07.170 --> 00:35:08.300
Please you, gentlemen,

697
00:35:08.300 --> 00:35:09.770
the time is unagreeable tothis business.

698
00:35:09.770 --> 00:35:11.830
Your importunacy ceasetill after dinner,

699
00:35:11.830 --> 00:35:13.200
that I may make HisLordship understand

700
00:35:13.200 --> 00:35:16.670
wherefore you are notpaid.

701
00:35:16.670 --> 00:35:17.970
Do so, my friends.

702
00:35:17.970 --> 00:35:19.000
Pray, you're welcome here.

703
00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:20.200
I'll speak with you anon.

704
00:35:29.830 --> 00:35:31.570
You make me marvel.

705
00:35:31.570 --> 00:35:32.700
Wherefore ere this time

706
00:35:32.700 --> 00:35:35.300
you had not fully laid mystate before me,

707
00:35:35.300 --> 00:35:36.870
that I might so have ratedmy expense,

708
00:35:36.870 --> 00:35:38.170
as I had leave of means?

709
00:35:38.170 --> 00:35:39.730
You would not hear me; atmany leisures, I proposed.

710
00:35:39.730 --> 00:35:42.330
Go to!

711
00:35:42.330 --> 00:35:45.170
Perchance some singlevantages you took

712
00:35:45.170 --> 00:35:47.300
when my indisposition putyou back,

713
00:35:47.300 --> 00:35:49.030
and that unaptness madeyour minister,

714
00:35:49.030 --> 00:35:50.600
thus to excuse yourself.

715
00:35:50.600 --> 00:35:54.030
Oh, my good lord, at many timesI brought in my accounts,

716
00:35:54.030 --> 00:35:55.330
laid them before you.

717
00:35:55.330 --> 00:35:56.400
You would throw them off

718
00:35:56.400 --> 00:35:58.670
and say you found them inmine honesty.

719
00:35:58.670 --> 00:36:00.800
When, for some triflingpresent, you have bid mereturn so much,

720
00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:02.770
I have shook my head andwept;

721
00:36:02.770 --> 00:36:04.200
Yea, against the authorityof manners,

722
00:36:04.200 --> 00:36:06.430
prayed you to hold yourhand more close.

723
00:36:06.430 --> 00:36:08.730
I have endured not seldom,nor no slight checks,

724
00:36:08.730 --> 00:36:10.570
when I have prompted youin the ebb of your estate

725
00:36:10.570 --> 00:36:12.300
and your great flow ofdebts.

726
00:36:12.300 --> 00:36:14.930
My loved lord, though youhear now too late

727
00:36:14.930 --> 00:36:16.430
yet now's a time

728
00:36:16.430 --> 00:36:18.630
the greatest of yourhaving lacks a half

729
00:36:18.630 --> 00:36:19.930
to pay your present debts.

730
00:36:21.770 --> 00:36:23.800
Let all my lands be sold.

731
00:36:23.800 --> 00:36:27.400
'tis all engaged, someforfeited and gone;

732
00:36:27.400 --> 00:36:30.130
and what remains willhardly stop the mouth ofpresent dues.

733
00:36:30.130 --> 00:36:31.200
The future comes apace.

734
00:36:31.200 --> 00:36:32.370
What shall defend theinterim?

735
00:36:32.370 --> 00:36:33.470
And at length, how goesour reckoning?

736
00:36:33.470 --> 00:36:35.530
To Lacedaemon did my landextend.

737
00:36:35.530 --> 00:36:38.130
O my good lord, the worldis but a word.

738
00:36:38.130 --> 00:36:39.830
Were it all yours to giveit in a breath,

739
00:36:39.830 --> 00:36:41.870
how quickly were it gone!

740
00:36:41.870 --> 00:36:43.000
You tell me true?

741
00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:45.330
If you suspect myhusbandry or falsehood,

742
00:36:45.330 --> 00:36:46.800
call me before theexactest auditors

743
00:36:46.800 --> 00:36:49.070
and set me on the proof.

744
00:36:49.070 --> 00:36:50.700
So the gods bless me,

745
00:36:50.700 --> 00:36:53.230
when all our offices havebeen oppressed withriotous feeders,

746
00:36:53.230 --> 00:36:56.400
when our vaults have weptwith drunken spilth of wine,

747
00:36:56.400 --> 00:36:58.200
when every room was blazedwith lights

748
00:36:58.200 --> 00:37:00.100
and brayed withminstrelsy,

749
00:37:00.100 --> 00:37:01.730
I have retired me to awasteful cock

750
00:37:01.730 --> 00:37:02.730
and set mine eyes at flow.

751
00:37:02.730 --> 00:37:03.900
Prithee, no more.

752
00:37:03.900 --> 00:37:06.130
Heavens, have I said, thebounty of this lord!

753
00:37:06.130 --> 00:37:08.430
How many prodigal bitshave slaves and peasants

754
00:37:08.430 --> 00:37:09.500
this night englutted!

755
00:37:09.500 --> 00:37:11.170
Who is not Timon's?

756
00:37:11.170 --> 00:37:15.630
What heart, head, sword, force,means, but is Lord Timon's?

757
00:37:15.630 --> 00:37:18.670
Great Timon, noble,worthy, royal Timon!

758
00:37:18.670 --> 00:37:22.230
Ah, when the means aregone that buy this praise,

759
00:37:22.230 --> 00:37:24.830
the breath is gone whereofthis praise is made.

760
00:37:24.830 --> 00:37:26.770
Feast-won, fast-lost;

761
00:37:26.770 --> 00:37:29.030
one cloud of winter showers,these flies are couched.

762
00:37:29.030 --> 00:37:31.530
Come, sermon me nofurther.

763
00:37:33.700 --> 00:37:38.000
No villainous bounty yethath passed my heart;

764
00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:41.630
unwisely, not ignobly,have I given.

765
00:37:43.170 --> 00:37:45.330
Why dost thou weep?

766
00:37:45.330 --> 00:37:50.230
Has thou the conscience lackto think I shall lack friends?

767
00:37:50.230 --> 00:37:52.930
Secure thy heart;

768
00:37:52.930 --> 00:37:55.070
if I would broach thevessels of my love,

769
00:37:55.070 --> 00:37:57.500
and try the arguments ofhearts by borrowing,

770
00:37:57.500 --> 00:38:00.470
men and men's fortunescould I frankly use

771
00:38:00.470 --> 00:38:02.100
as I can bid thee speak.

772
00:38:02.100 --> 00:38:04.300
Assurance bless yourthoughts!

773
00:38:04.300 --> 00:38:07.500
And, in some sort, thesewants of mine are crowned,

774
00:38:07.500 --> 00:38:09.830
that I account themblessings;

775
00:38:09.830 --> 00:38:13.400
for by these shall I tryfriends.

776
00:38:13.400 --> 00:38:17.230
You shall see how youmistake my fortunes;

777
00:38:17.230 --> 00:38:20.370
I am wealthy in myfriends.

778
00:38:20.370 --> 00:38:21.570
Within there!

779
00:38:21.570 --> 00:38:22.570
Flaminius!

780
00:38:22.570 --> 00:38:23.630
My lord?

781
00:38:23.630 --> 00:38:24.630
Servilius!

782
00:38:24.630 --> 00:38:25.670
My lord?

783
00:38:28.270 --> 00:38:31.070
I will dispatch youseverally;

784
00:38:31.070 --> 00:38:33.030
To Lord Lucius, you;

785
00:38:33.030 --> 00:38:35.830
to Lord Lucullus, you.

786
00:38:35.830 --> 00:38:38.200
I hunted with His Honortoday.

787
00:38:38.200 --> 00:38:40.500
To Sempronius, you.

788
00:38:40.500 --> 00:38:44.230
Commend me to their loves,and, I am proud, say,

789
00:38:44.230 --> 00:38:46.770
that my occasions havefound time to use 'em

790
00:38:46.770 --> 00:38:48.530
toward a supply of money.

791
00:38:48.530 --> 00:38:53.230
Let the request be...fifty talents?

792
00:38:53.230 --> 00:38:54.500
As you have said, my lord.

793
00:38:54.500 --> 00:38:56.900
Lord Lucius and Lucullus,hmm?

794
00:38:56.900 --> 00:38:59.300
And go you, sir, to thesenators

795
00:38:59.300 --> 00:39:01.530
of whom, even to thestate's best health,

796
00:39:01.530 --> 00:39:03.230
I have deserved thishearing

797
00:39:03.230 --> 00:39:05.830
bid 'em send of the instanta thousand talents to me.

798
00:39:05.830 --> 00:39:07.070
I have been bold

799
00:39:07.070 --> 00:39:08.800
for that I knew it themost general way

800
00:39:08.800 --> 00:39:11.100
to them to use your signetand your name;

801
00:39:11.100 --> 00:39:12.370
but they do shake theirheads,

802
00:39:12.370 --> 00:39:16.630
and I am here no richer inreturn.

803
00:39:16.630 --> 00:39:19.470
It is true?

804
00:39:19.470 --> 00:39:21.070
Can it be?

805
00:39:21.070 --> 00:39:23.030
They answer, in a jointand corporate voice,

806
00:39:23.030 --> 00:39:25.130
that now they are at fall,want treasure,

807
00:39:25.130 --> 00:39:26.130
cannot do what they would;

808
00:39:26.130 --> 00:39:28.130
are sorry you arehonorable

809
00:39:28.130 --> 00:39:29.400
but yet they could havewished

810
00:39:29.400 --> 00:39:31.470
they know not somethinghath been amiss

811
00:39:31.470 --> 00:39:33.730
a noble nature may catch awrench

812
00:39:33.730 --> 00:39:35.970
would all were well  'tispity;

813
00:39:35.970 --> 00:39:37.730
and so, intending otherserious matters,

814
00:39:37.730 --> 00:39:40.700
after distasteful looksand these hard fractions,

815
00:39:40.700 --> 00:39:44.200
with certain half-caps andcold-moving nods

816
00:39:44.200 --> 00:39:45.570
they froze me intosilence.

817
00:39:48.870 --> 00:39:50.370
You gods, reward them!

818
00:39:54.330 --> 00:39:56.030
Prithee, man, lookcheerly.

819
00:39:57.700 --> 00:40:02.530
These old fellows have theiringratitude in them hereditary.

820
00:40:02.530 --> 00:40:08.000
Their blood is caked, 'tiscold, it seldom flows;

821
00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:12.000
'tis lack of kindly warmththey are not kind;

822
00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:14.400
and nature, as it growsagain toward earth,

823
00:40:14.400 --> 00:40:19.800
is fashioned for thejourney, dull and heavy.

824
00:40:19.800 --> 00:40:22.230
Go to Ventidius.

825
00:40:22.230 --> 00:40:24.600
Prithee, be not sad.

826
00:40:24.600 --> 00:40:25.800
Ingeniously I speak.

827
00:40:25.800 --> 00:40:27.970
No blame belongs to thee.

828
00:40:27.970 --> 00:40:30.770
Ventidius lately buriedhis father,

829
00:40:30.770 --> 00:40:33.700
by whose death he's steppedinto a great estate.

830
00:40:33.700 --> 00:40:37.030
When he was poor, imprisoned,and in scarcity of friends,

831
00:40:37.030 --> 00:40:38.900
I cleared him with fivetalents.

832
00:40:38.900 --> 00:40:40.400
Greet him from me;

833
00:40:40.400 --> 00:40:42.630
bid him suppose some goodnecessity touches his friend,

834
00:40:42.630 --> 00:40:45.100
which craves to be rememberedwith those five talents.

835
00:40:45.100 --> 00:40:49.930
That had, give it these fellowsto whom 'tis instant due.

836
00:40:49.930 --> 00:40:53.130
Ne'er speak, or think,that Timon's fortunes

837
00:40:53.130 --> 00:40:56.770
amongst his friends can sink.

838
00:40:56.770 --> 00:40:59.400
I would I could not think it.

839
00:40:59.400 --> 00:41:01.100
That thought isbounty's foe;

840
00:41:01.100 --> 00:41:04.000
being free itself, itthinks all others so.

841
00:41:33.470 --> 00:41:37.500
Flaminius, honest Flaminius;

842
00:41:37.500 --> 00:41:41.000
you are very respectivelywelcome, sir.

843
00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:43.330
And how does thathonorable, complete,

844
00:41:43.330 --> 00:41:45.230
free-hearted gentleman ofAthens,

845
00:41:45.230 --> 00:41:47.930
thy very bountiful goodlord and master?

846
00:41:47.930 --> 00:41:49.600
His health is well sir.

847
00:41:49.600 --> 00:41:52.630
I am right glad that hishealth is well, sir.

848
00:41:52.630 --> 00:41:55.800
And what hast thou thereunder thy cloak, prettyFlaminius?

849
00:41:55.800 --> 00:41:58.430
'Faith, nothing but anempty box, sir;

850
00:41:58.430 --> 00:41:59.870
Which, in my lord'sbehalf,

851
00:41:59.870 --> 00:42:02.130
I come to entreat YourHonor to supply;

852
00:42:02.130 --> 00:42:05.100
who, having great and instantoccasion to use fifty talents,

853
00:42:05.100 --> 00:42:06.830
hath sent to Your Lordshipto furnish him,

854
00:42:06.830 --> 00:42:10.200
nothing doubting yourpresent assistance therein.

855
00:42:10.200 --> 00:42:11.470
La, la!

856
00:42:18.230 --> 00:42:20.800
La, la, la!

857
00:42:20.800 --> 00:42:23.370
"Nothing doubting," says he?

858
00:42:23.370 --> 00:42:25.130
Alas, good lord!

859
00:42:25.130 --> 00:42:26.870
A noble gentleman 'tis,

860
00:42:26.870 --> 00:42:29.530
if he would not keep sogood a house.

861
00:42:29.530 --> 00:42:31.700
Many a time and often Ihave dined with him,

862
00:42:31.700 --> 00:42:34.500
and told him on it, and comeagain to supper to him,

863
00:42:34.500 --> 00:42:37.330
of purpose to have himspend less,

864
00:42:37.330 --> 00:42:39.070
and yet he would embraceno counsel,

865
00:42:39.070 --> 00:42:40.970
take no warning by mycoming.

866
00:42:40.970 --> 00:42:43.500
Every man has his fault,and honesty is his.

867
00:42:43.500 --> 00:42:44.630
I had told him on it,

868
00:42:44.630 --> 00:42:47.700
but I could ne'er get himfrom it.

869
00:42:47.700 --> 00:42:52.070
Flaminius, I have notedthee always wise.

870
00:42:52.070 --> 00:42:53.530
Your Lordship speaks yourpleasure.

871
00:42:53.530 --> 00:42:56.430
I have observed theealways for a towardlyprompt spirit

872
00:42:56.430 --> 00:42:57.670
give thee thy due

873
00:42:57.670 --> 00:42:59.600
and one that knows whatbelongs to reason;

874
00:42:59.600 --> 00:43:02.670
and canst use the time well,if the time use thee well.

875
00:43:02.670 --> 00:43:04.830
Good parts in thee.

876
00:43:04.830 --> 00:43:08.100
Draw nearer, honestFlaminius.

877
00:43:08.100 --> 00:43:10.170
Thy lord's a bountifulgentleman.

878
00:43:10.170 --> 00:43:11.630
But thou art wise;

879
00:43:11.630 --> 00:43:13.770
and thou knowest wellenough, although thoucomest to me,

880
00:43:13.770 --> 00:43:16.100
that this is no time tolend money,

881
00:43:16.100 --> 00:43:19.770
especially upon barefriendship, without security.

882
00:43:19.770 --> 00:43:24.570
Here's three solidares forthee.

883
00:43:24.570 --> 00:43:29.200
Good boy, wink at me, andsay thou sawest me not.

884
00:43:29.200 --> 00:43:30.830
Fare thee well.

885
00:43:30.830 --> 00:43:33.070
Is it possible the worldshould so much differ,

886
00:43:33.070 --> 00:43:35.670
and we alive that lived?

887
00:43:35.670 --> 00:43:38.670
Fly, damned baseness, tohim that worships thee!

888
00:43:38.670 --> 00:43:39.900
Ha!

889
00:43:39.900 --> 00:43:42.430
Now I see thou art a fooland fit for thy master.

890
00:43:42.430 --> 00:43:45.400
May these add to the numberthat may scald thee!

891
00:43:45.400 --> 00:43:47.470
Let molten coin be thydamnation,

892
00:43:47.470 --> 00:43:49.370
thou disease of a friend,and not himself!

893
00:43:49.370 --> 00:43:51.870
Has friendship such afaint and milky heart,

894
00:43:51.870 --> 00:43:53.800
it turns in less than twonights?

895
00:43:53.800 --> 00:43:55.970
Oh, you gods, I feelmaster's passion!

896
00:43:55.970 --> 00:44:00.100
This slave, unto his honor,has my lord's meat in him.

897
00:44:00.100 --> 00:44:02.000
Why should it thrive andturn to nutriment,

898
00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:03.830
when he is turned topoison?

899
00:44:03.830 --> 00:44:05.900
Oh, may diseases only workupon it!

900
00:44:05.900 --> 00:44:08.800
And when he's sick todeath, let not that partof nature

901
00:44:08.800 --> 00:44:10.100
which my lord paid for

902
00:44:10.100 --> 00:44:11.900
be of any power to expelsickness,

903
00:44:11.900 --> 00:44:13.600
but prolong his hour!

904
00:44:22.470 --> 00:44:23.600
Servilius!

905
00:44:23.600 --> 00:44:25.700
You are kindly met, sir.

906
00:44:25.700 --> 00:44:28.170
Commend me to thyhonorable virtuous lord,

907
00:44:28.170 --> 00:44:30.330
my very exquisite friend.

908
00:44:30.330 --> 00:44:32.200
May it please Your Honor,my lord hath sent

909
00:44:32.200 --> 00:44:33.970
Ha! What has he sent?

910
00:44:33.970 --> 00:44:36.700
I am so much endeared tothat lord;

911
00:44:36.700 --> 00:44:38.070
he's ever sending.

912
00:44:38.070 --> 00:44:40.570
How shall I thank him,thinkest thou?

913
00:44:40.570 --> 00:44:42.830
And what has he sent now?

914
00:44:42.830 --> 00:44:46.770
Has only sent his presentoccasion now, my lord;

915
00:44:46.770 --> 00:44:49.000
requesting Your Lordshipto supply his instant use

916
00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:50.130
with so many talents.

917
00:44:52.430 --> 00:44:56.070
I know His Lordship is butmerry with me;

918
00:44:56.070 --> 00:44:59.900
he cannot want 5,500talents.

919
00:44:59.900 --> 00:45:02.870
But in the meantime, hewants less, my lord.

920
00:45:02.870 --> 00:45:04.400
If his occasion were notvirtuous,

921
00:45:04.400 --> 00:45:07.100
I should not urge it halfso faithfully.

922
00:45:07.100 --> 00:45:08.770
Dost thou speak seriously,Servilius?

923
00:45:08.770 --> 00:45:10.200
Upon my soul, 'tis true,sir.

924
00:45:14.300 --> 00:45:17.770
What a wicked beast was Ito disfurnish myself

925
00:45:17.770 --> 00:45:19.530
against such a good time,

926
00:45:19.530 --> 00:45:23.030
when I might have shownmyself honorable.

927
00:45:23.030 --> 00:45:25.970
How unluckily it happened,that I should purchase

928
00:45:25.970 --> 00:45:28.630
the day before for alittle part

929
00:45:28.630 --> 00:45:33.970
and undo a great deal ofhonor.

930
00:45:33.970 --> 00:45:37.500
Servilius, now, before thegods, I am not able to do

931
00:45:37.500 --> 00:45:39.730
the more beast, I say.

932
00:45:39.730 --> 00:45:43.800
I was sending to use LordTimon myself,

933
00:45:43.800 --> 00:45:46.770
But I would not for thewealth of Athens I haddone it now.

934
00:45:49.800 --> 00:45:51.700
Commend me bountifully toHis good Lordship;

935
00:45:51.700 --> 00:45:54.600
and I hope His Honor willconceive the fairest of me,

936
00:45:54.600 --> 00:45:57.230
because I have no power tobe kind.

937
00:46:01.470 --> 00:46:06.000
And tell him this from me,

938
00:46:06.000 --> 00:46:11.070
I count it one of mygreatest afflictions, say,

939
00:46:11.070 --> 00:46:16.670
that I cannot pleasure suchan honorable gentleman.

940
00:46:18.400 --> 00:46:21.830
Good Servilius, will youbefriend me so far

941
00:46:21.830 --> 00:46:25.500
as to use mine own wordsto him?

942
00:46:25.500 --> 00:46:26.700
Yes, sir, I shall.

943
00:46:30.470 --> 00:46:34.470
I'll look you out a goodturn,

944
00:46:34.470 --> 00:46:35.530
Servilius.

945
00:46:42.800 --> 00:46:45.930
Must he needs trouble mein it, hmm,

946
00:46:45.930 --> 00:46:48.270
above all others?

947
00:46:48.270 --> 00:46:52.170
He might have tried LordLucius or Lucullus;

948
00:46:52.170 --> 00:46:54.300
and now Ventidius iswealthy too,

949
00:46:54.300 --> 00:46:56.170
whom he redeemed fromprison.

950
00:46:56.170 --> 00:46:58.070
all these owe theirestates unto him.

951
00:46:58.070 --> 00:47:00.500
My lord, they've all beentouched and found base metal,

952
00:47:00.500 --> 00:47:03.030
for they have all deniedhim.

953
00:47:03.030 --> 00:47:04.570
How!

954
00:47:04.570 --> 00:47:06.330
Have they denied him?

955
00:47:06.330 --> 00:47:09.230
Has Ventidius and Lucullusdenied him?

956
00:47:09.230 --> 00:47:11.330
And does he send to me?

957
00:47:11.330 --> 00:47:12.430
Three?

958
00:47:12.430 --> 00:47:13.800
Hum!

959
00:47:13.800 --> 00:47:16.970
It shows but little loveor judgment in him.

960
00:47:16.970 --> 00:47:19.870
Must I be his last refuge?

961
00:47:19.870 --> 00:47:23.600
His friends, like physicians,thrice give him over.

962
00:47:23.600 --> 00:47:26.500
Must I take the cure uponme?

963
00:47:26.500 --> 00:47:29.070
Has much disgraced me init;

964
00:47:29.070 --> 00:47:32.770
I'm angry at him, thatmight have known my place.

965
00:47:32.770 --> 00:47:34.330
I see no sense for it,

966
00:47:34.330 --> 00:47:36.970
but his occasions mighthave wooed me first;

967
00:47:36.970 --> 00:47:38.800
for, in my conscience, Iwas the first man

968
00:47:38.800 --> 00:47:41.270
that e'er received giftfrom him.

969
00:47:41.270 --> 00:47:44.730
And does he think sobackwardly of me now

970
00:47:44.730 --> 00:47:46.670
that I'll requite it last?

971
00:47:46.670 --> 00:47:48.500
No.

972
00:47:48.500 --> 00:47:51.200
So it may prove an argumentof laughter to the rest,

973
00:47:51.200 --> 00:47:55.000
and I amongst the lords bethought a fool.

974
00:47:55.000 --> 00:47:57.270
I'd rather than the worthof thrice the sum

975
00:47:57.270 --> 00:48:00.730
had sent to me first, butfor my mind's sake;

976
00:48:00.730 --> 00:48:04.000
I'd such a courage to dohim good.

977
00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:10.270
But now return, and with theirfaint reply this answer join:

978
00:48:10.270 --> 00:48:13.400
who bates mine honor shallnot know my coin.

979
00:48:15.530 --> 00:48:16.730
One of Lord Timon's men.

980
00:48:16.730 --> 00:48:17.900
Flaminius!

981
00:48:17.900 --> 00:48:19.100
Sir, a word.

982
00:48:19.100 --> 00:48:21.000
Pray, is my lord ready tocome forth?

983
00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:22.100
No, indeed, he is not.

984
00:48:22.100 --> 00:48:23.230
We attend His Lordship;

985
00:48:23.230 --> 00:48:24.230
pray, signify so much.

986
00:48:24.230 --> 00:48:25.230
I need not tell him that!

987
00:48:25.230 --> 00:48:26.230
He knows you are toodiligent.

988
00:48:26.230 --> 00:48:27.270
Is not that his stewardmuffled so?

989
00:48:27.270 --> 00:48:28.400
He goes away in a cloud.

990
00:48:28.400 --> 00:48:29.400
Call him.

991
00:48:29.400 --> 00:48:30.570
Ho! Do you hear, sir?

992
00:48:30.570 --> 00:48:31.800
By your leave, sir,

993
00:48:31.800 --> 00:48:33.500
What do ye ask of me, myfriend?

994
00:48:33.500 --> 00:48:35.430
We wait for certain moneyhere, sir.

995
00:48:35.430 --> 00:48:37.430
Ay, if money were ascertain as your waiting,

996
00:48:37.430 --> 00:48:38.900
'twere sure enough.

997
00:48:38.900 --> 00:48:41.030
Why then preferred you notyour sums and bills,

998
00:48:41.030 --> 00:48:43.830
when your false masterseat of my lord's meat?

999
00:48:43.830 --> 00:48:45.570
Then they could smile andfawn upon his debts

1000
00:48:45.570 --> 00:48:49.270
and take down the interestinto their gluttonous maws.

1001
00:48:49.270 --> 00:48:51.230
You do yourselves butwrong to stir me up.

1002
00:48:51.230 --> 00:48:53.370
Let me pass quietly.

1003
00:48:53.370 --> 00:48:55.930
Believe it, my lord and Ihave made an end;

1004
00:48:55.930 --> 00:48:58.030
I have no more to reckon,he to spend.

1005
00:48:58.030 --> 00:49:00.270
Ay, but this answer willnot serve.

1006
00:49:00.270 --> 00:49:02.130
If 'twill not serve, 'tisnot so base as you;

1007
00:49:02.130 --> 00:49:03.930
For you serve knaves.

1008
00:49:03.930 --> 00:49:05.770
How, what does hiscashiered worship mutter?

1009
00:49:05.770 --> 00:49:07.730
No matter what; he's poor,and that's revenge enough.

1010
00:49:07.730 --> 00:49:08.970
Here comes Servilius;

1011
00:49:08.970 --> 00:49:12.600
now we shall know someanswer.

1012
00:49:12.600 --> 00:49:14.330
If I might beseech you,gentlemen,

1013
00:49:14.330 --> 00:49:15.470
to repair some other hour,

1014
00:49:15.470 --> 00:49:17.030
I should derivemuch from it;

1015
00:49:17.030 --> 00:49:18.570
for take it of my soul,

1016
00:49:18.570 --> 00:49:20.600
my lord leans wondrouslyto discontent.

1017
00:49:20.600 --> 00:49:22.530
His comfortable temper hasforsook him;

1018
00:49:22.530 --> 00:49:24.400
he's much out of healthand keeps his chamber.

1019
00:49:24.400 --> 00:49:26.430
Many who keep theirchambers are not sick.

1020
00:49:26.430 --> 00:49:28.770
And if it be so far beyondhis health,

1021
00:49:28.770 --> 00:49:31.600
methinks he should thesooner pay his debts

1022
00:49:31.600 --> 00:49:33.470
and make a clear way tothe gods.

1023
00:49:33.470 --> 00:49:34.800
We cannot take this foranswer, sir.

1024
00:49:34.800 --> 00:49:36.400
Aah!

1025
00:49:36.400 --> 00:49:39.770
Are my doors opposedagainst my passage?

1026
00:49:39.770 --> 00:49:41.470
Have I been ever free,

1027
00:49:41.470 --> 00:49:45.000
and must my house now be myretentive enemy, my jail?

1028
00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:48.600
The place which I have feasted,does it now, like all mankind,

1029
00:49:48.600 --> 00:49:49.670
show me an iron heart?

1030
00:49:49.670 --> 00:49:50.730
My lord, here is my bill.

1031
00:49:50.730 --> 00:49:51.730
Here's mine.

1032
00:49:51.730 --> 00:49:52.730
And mine, my lord.

1033
00:49:52.730 --> 00:49:53.730
Knock me down with 'em.

1034
00:49:53.730 --> 00:49:54.730
Cleave me to the girdle.

1035
00:49:54.730 --> 00:49:55.730
Alas, my lord

1036
00:49:55.730 --> 00:49:56.730
Cut my heart in sums.

1037
00:49:56.730 --> 00:49:57.730
Mine, fifty talents.

1038
00:49:57.730 --> 00:49:58.730
Tell out my blood!

1039
00:49:58.730 --> 00:49:59.730
Five thousand crowns, my lord.

1040
00:49:59.730 --> 00:50:00.730
Five thousand drops pays that.

1041
00:50:00.730 --> 00:50:01.730
What's yours?

1042
00:50:01.730 --> 00:50:03.200
Alas, my lord

1043
00:50:03.200 --> 00:50:07.170
The gods fall upon you!

1044
00:50:07.170 --> 00:50:12.470
They have even put mybreath from me, the slaves.

1045
00:50:12.470 --> 00:50:14.470
Creditors?

1046
00:50:14.470 --> 00:50:15.470
Devils!

1047
00:50:15.470 --> 00:50:17.570
My dear lord

1048
00:50:17.570 --> 00:50:18.630
What if it should be so?

1049
00:50:18.630 --> 00:50:20.930
My lord

1050
00:50:20.930 --> 00:50:23.200
I'll have it so.

1051
00:50:23.200 --> 00:50:24.370
My steward!

1052
00:50:24.370 --> 00:50:26.870
Here, my lord.

1053
00:50:26.870 --> 00:50:29.200
So fitly?

1054
00:50:29.200 --> 00:50:34.130
Go, bid all my friendsagain,

1055
00:50:34.130 --> 00:50:38.870
Lucius, Lucullus, andSempronius.

1056
00:50:38.870 --> 00:50:41.230
All.

1057
00:50:41.230 --> 00:50:43.030
I'll once more feast therascals.

1058
00:50:43.030 --> 00:50:45.130
O my lord, you only speakfrom your distracted soul;

1059
00:50:45.130 --> 00:50:47.830
there is not so much left tofurnish out a moderate table.

1060
00:50:47.830 --> 00:50:50.430
Be it not in thy care.

1061
00:50:50.430 --> 00:50:53.970
Go, I charge thee, invitethem all.

1062
00:50:53.970 --> 00:50:56.870
Let in the tide of knavesonce more;

1063
00:50:56.870 --> 00:50:58.730
my cook and I'll provide.

1064
00:51:19.770 --> 00:51:23.030
My lord, you have my voiceto it;

1065
00:51:23.030 --> 00:51:24.600
the fault's Bloody;

1066
00:51:24.600 --> 00:51:26.770
'tis necessary he shoulddie.

1067
00:51:26.770 --> 00:51:29.270
Nothing emboldens sin somuch as mercy.

1068
00:51:29.270 --> 00:51:30.270
Most true.

1069
00:51:30.270 --> 00:51:33.070
The law shall bruise him.

1070
00:51:33.070 --> 00:51:38.600
Honor, health, andcompassion to the senate.

1071
00:51:38.600 --> 00:51:41.400
Now, Captain?

1072
00:51:41.400 --> 00:51:44.370
I am an humble suitor toyour virtues;

1073
00:51:44.370 --> 00:51:47.400
for pity is the virtue ofthe law,

1074
00:51:47.400 --> 00:51:52.130
and none but tyrants useit cruelly.

1075
00:51:52.130 --> 00:51:56.230
It pleases time andfortune to lie heavy

1076
00:51:56.230 --> 00:51:57.970
upon a friend of mine,who, in hot blood,

1077
00:51:57.970 --> 00:51:59.270
hath stepped into the law,

1078
00:51:59.270 --> 00:52:01.870
which is past depth tothose that, without heed,

1079
00:52:01.870 --> 00:52:04.100
do plunge into it.

1080
00:52:04.100 --> 00:52:08.200
He is a man, setting his fateaside, of comely virtues.

1081
00:52:08.200 --> 00:52:10.630
Nor did he soil the factwith cowardice

1082
00:52:10.630 --> 00:52:13.130
an honor in him which buysout his fault

1083
00:52:13.130 --> 00:52:15.500
but with a noble fury andfair spirit,

1084
00:52:15.500 --> 00:52:17.870
seeing his reputationtouched to death,

1085
00:52:17.870 --> 00:52:19.900
he did oppose his foe.

1086
00:52:19.900 --> 00:52:22.030
And with such sober andunnoted passion,

1087
00:52:22.030 --> 00:52:23.200
he did behoove his anger,

1088
00:52:23.200 --> 00:52:24.600
ere 'twas spent,

1089
00:52:24.600 --> 00:52:26.900
as if he had but proved anargument.

1090
00:52:26.900 --> 00:52:29.500
You undergo too strict aparadox,

1091
00:52:29.500 --> 00:52:32.670
striving to make an uglydeed look fair.

1092
00:52:32.670 --> 00:52:34.400
Your words have took suchpains

1093
00:52:34.400 --> 00:52:37.870
as if they labored to bringmanslaughter into form

1094
00:52:37.870 --> 00:52:39.700
and set quarrelling uponthe head of valor;

1095
00:52:39.700 --> 00:52:42.970
which indeed is valor misbegotand came into the world

1096
00:52:42.970 --> 00:52:46.930
when sects and factionswere newly born.

1097
00:52:46.930 --> 00:52:49.830
He's truly valiant thatcan wisely suffer

1098
00:52:49.830 --> 00:52:51.630
the worst that man canbreathe

1099
00:52:51.630 --> 00:52:53.130
and make his wrongs hisoutsides,

1100
00:52:53.130 --> 00:52:55.870
to wear them like hisraiment, carelessly,

1101
00:52:55.870 --> 00:52:58.570
and ne'er prefer hisinjuries to his heart,

1102
00:52:58.570 --> 00:53:00.970
to bring it into danger.

1103
00:53:00.970 --> 00:53:03.870
If wrongs be evils andenforce us kill,

1104
00:53:03.870 --> 00:53:07.000
what folly 'tis to hazardlife for ill!

1105
00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:08.100
My lord

1106
00:53:08.100 --> 00:53:09.200
You cannot make gross sinslook clear.

1107
00:53:09.200 --> 00:53:10.230
My lord!

1108
00:53:10.230 --> 00:53:13.430
To revenge is no valor,but to bear.

1109
00:53:13.430 --> 00:53:14.500
My lords, then, underfavor,

1110
00:53:14.500 --> 00:53:17.170
pardon me, if I speak likea captain.

1111
00:53:17.170 --> 00:53:19.370
Why do fond men exposethemselves to battle,

1112
00:53:19.370 --> 00:53:21.330
and not endure allthreats?

1113
00:53:21.330 --> 00:53:24.530
Sleep upon it, and let the foesquietly cut their throats,

1114
00:53:24.530 --> 00:53:26.470
without repugnancy?

1115
00:53:26.470 --> 00:53:27.900
If there be such valor inthe bearing,

1116
00:53:27.900 --> 00:53:29.770
what make we abroad?

1117
00:53:29.770 --> 00:53:32.570
Why then, women are morevaliant that stay at home,

1118
00:53:32.570 --> 00:53:34.500
if bearing carry it,

1119
00:53:34.500 --> 00:53:38.630
and the ass more captainthan the lion,

1120
00:53:38.630 --> 00:53:40.930
the fellow loaden withirons wiser than the judge,

1121
00:53:40.930 --> 00:53:44.230
if wisdom be in suffering.

1122
00:53:44.230 --> 00:53:50.130
O my lords, as you aregreat, be pitifully good.

1123
00:53:50.130 --> 00:53:52.530
Who cannot condemnrashness in cold blood?

1124
00:53:52.530 --> 00:53:55.100
To kill, I grant, is sin'sextremest gust;

1125
00:53:55.100 --> 00:53:57.970
but, in defence, by mercy,'tis most just.

1126
00:53:57.970 --> 00:54:00.300
To be in anger is impiety;

1127
00:54:00.300 --> 00:54:02.800
but who is man that is notangry?

1128
00:54:02.800 --> 00:54:04.470
Weigh but the crime withthis.

1129
00:54:04.470 --> 00:54:06.570
You breathe in vain.

1130
00:54:06.570 --> 00:54:08.330
In vain!

1131
00:54:08.330 --> 00:54:10.600
His service done atLacedaemon and Byzantium

1132
00:54:10.600 --> 00:54:12.270
were a sufficient briberfor his life.

1133
00:54:12.270 --> 00:54:13.370
What's that?

1134
00:54:13.370 --> 00:54:14.630
I say, my lords, he hasdone fair service,

1135
00:54:14.630 --> 00:54:16.530
and slain in fight many ofyour enemies.

1136
00:54:16.530 --> 00:54:18.970
How full of valor did he bearhimself in the last conflict,

1137
00:54:18.970 --> 00:54:20.730
and made plenteous wounds!

1138
00:54:20.730 --> 00:54:22.430
He has made too muchplenty with 'em;

1139
00:54:22.430 --> 00:54:24.230
he's a sworn rioter.

1140
00:54:24.230 --> 00:54:25.870
He has a sin that oftendrowns him

1141
00:54:25.870 --> 00:54:27.370
and takes his valorprisoner.

1142
00:54:27.370 --> 00:54:28.570
If there were no foes,

1143
00:54:28.570 --> 00:54:30.170
that were enough toovercome him.

1144
00:54:30.170 --> 00:54:33.330
In the beastly fury, he hasbeen known to commit outrages

1145
00:54:33.330 --> 00:54:35.300
and cherish factions.

1146
00:54:35.300 --> 00:54:36.700
It is inferred to us

1147
00:54:36.700 --> 00:54:39.770
that his days are foul andhis drink dangerous.

1148
00:54:39.770 --> 00:54:41.830
He dies.

1149
00:54:41.830 --> 00:54:43.900
Hard fate!

1150
00:54:43.900 --> 00:54:46.970
He might have died in war.

1151
00:54:46.970 --> 00:54:48.700
My lords, if not for anyparts in him

1152
00:54:48.700 --> 00:54:50.430
though his right arm mightpurchase his own time

1153
00:54:50.430 --> 00:54:51.700
and be in debt to none

1154
00:54:51.700 --> 00:54:53.330
yet more to move you,

1155
00:54:53.330 --> 00:54:55.330
take my deserts to his,and join 'em both.

1156
00:54:55.330 --> 00:54:57.830
And, for I know yourreverend ages love security,

1157
00:54:57.830 --> 00:55:01.770
I'll pawn my victories,all my honors to you,

1158
00:55:01.770 --> 00:55:03.600
upon his good returns.

1159
00:55:03.600 --> 00:55:05.670
If, by this crime, he owesthe law his life,

1160
00:55:05.670 --> 00:55:08.300
why, let the war receiveit in valiant gore

1161
00:55:08.300 --> 00:55:11.770
for law is strict, and waris nothing more.

1162
00:55:11.770 --> 00:55:14.800
We are for law.

1163
00:55:14.800 --> 00:55:15.970
He dies.

1164
00:55:15.970 --> 00:55:18.000
Urge it no more, on heightof our displeasure.

1165
00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:19.300
Friend or brother,

1166
00:55:19.300 --> 00:55:22.570
he forfeits his own bloodthat spills another.

1167
00:55:22.570 --> 00:55:24.100
Must it be so?

1168
00:55:24.100 --> 00:55:25.470
It must not be.

1169
00:55:25.470 --> 00:55:26.930
My lords, I do beseechyou, know me.

1170
00:55:26.930 --> 00:55:27.930
How!

1171
00:55:27.930 --> 00:55:28.930
Call me to yourremembrances.

1172
00:55:28.930 --> 00:55:30.070
What!

1173
00:55:30.070 --> 00:55:31.430
I cannot think but thatyour age has forgot me;

1174
00:55:31.430 --> 00:55:33.900
it could not else be, Ishould prove so base, to sue,

1175
00:55:33.900 --> 00:55:35.700
and be denied such commongrace.

1176
00:55:35.700 --> 00:55:37.070
My wounds ache at you.

1177
00:55:37.070 --> 00:55:39.870
Do you dare our anger?

1178
00:55:39.870 --> 00:55:43.630
'Tis in few words, butspacious in effect;

1179
00:55:43.630 --> 00:55:46.570
we banish thee forever.

1180
00:55:46.570 --> 00:55:48.230
Banish me!

1181
00:55:48.230 --> 00:55:50.270
Banish your dotage;

1182
00:55:50.270 --> 00:55:52.430
banish usury, that makesthe senate ugly.

1183
00:55:52.430 --> 00:55:55.170
If, after two days' shine,Athens contain thee,

1184
00:55:55.170 --> 00:55:56.830
attend our weightierjudgment.

1185
00:55:56.830 --> 00:56:02.300
And, not to swell ourspirit, he shall beexecuted presently.

1186
00:56:02.300 --> 00:56:03.830
Now the gods keep you oldenough;

1187
00:56:03.830 --> 00:56:07.170
that you may live only inbone, that none may lookon you!

1188
00:56:09.900 --> 00:56:12.530
I'm worse than mad.

1189
00:56:12.530 --> 00:56:14.530
I have kept back theirfoes,

1190
00:56:14.530 --> 00:56:16.770
while they have told theirmoney

1191
00:56:16.770 --> 00:56:19.270
and let out their coinupon large interest,

1192
00:56:19.270 --> 00:56:22.900
I myself rich only inlarge hurts.

1193
00:56:22.900 --> 00:56:27.200
All those for this?

1194
00:56:27.200 --> 00:56:29.370
Is this the balsam thatthe usuring senate

1195
00:56:29.370 --> 00:56:31.570
pours into captains'wounds?

1196
00:56:31.570 --> 00:56:35.200
Banishment.

1197
00:56:35.200 --> 00:56:37.670
It comes not ill;

1198
00:56:37.670 --> 00:56:39.970
I hate not to be banished;

1199
00:56:39.970 --> 00:56:42.730
it is a cause worthy myspleen and fury

1200
00:56:42.730 --> 00:56:47.300
that I may strike atAthens.

1201
00:56:47.300 --> 00:56:48.770
I'll cheer up mydiscontented troops

1202
00:56:48.770 --> 00:56:51.100
and lay for hearts.

1203
00:56:51.100 --> 00:56:55.770
'Tis honor with most landsto be at odds;

1204
00:56:55.770 --> 00:56:59.700
soldiers should brook aslittle wrongs as gods.

1205
00:57:11.800 --> 00:57:13.930
The good time of day toyou, sir.

1206
00:57:13.930 --> 00:57:17.130
I also wish it to you.

1207
00:57:17.130 --> 00:57:22.070
I think this honorable lorddid but try us this other day.

1208
00:57:22.070 --> 00:57:24.100
Upon that were my thoughtstiring,

1209
00:57:24.100 --> 00:57:26.600
when we encountered.

1210
00:57:26.600 --> 00:57:30.000
I hope it is not so lowwith him

1211
00:57:30.000 --> 00:57:34.800
as he made it seem in thetrial of his several friends.

1212
00:57:34.800 --> 00:57:35.900
It should not be,

1213
00:57:35.900 --> 00:57:39.030
by the persuasion of hisnew feasting.

1214
00:57:39.030 --> 00:57:41.900
I should think so.

1215
00:57:41.900 --> 00:57:44.900
He hath sent me an earnestinviting,

1216
00:57:44.900 --> 00:57:49.370
which many my near occasionsdid urge me to put off;

1217
00:57:49.370 --> 00:57:52.000
but he hath conjured mebeyond them,

1218
00:57:52.000 --> 00:57:54.770
and I must needs appear.

1219
00:57:54.770 --> 00:57:57.730
In like manner was I in debtto my importunate business,

1220
00:57:57.730 --> 00:58:02.000
but he would not hear myexcuse.

1221
00:58:02.000 --> 00:58:06.070
I am sorry, when he sentto borrow of me,

1222
00:58:06.070 --> 00:58:08.370
that my provision was out.

1223
00:58:08.370 --> 00:58:10.700
I am sick of that grieftoo,

1224
00:58:10.700 --> 00:58:13.830
as I understand how allthings go.

1225
00:58:13.830 --> 00:58:16.800
Every man here's so.

1226
00:58:16.800 --> 00:58:20.330
What would he haveborrowed of you?

1227
00:58:20.330 --> 00:58:22.400
A thousand pieces.

1228
00:58:26.500 --> 00:58:29.200
He sent to me, sir

1229
00:58:29.200 --> 00:58:30.400
Here he comes.

1230
00:58:33.230 --> 00:58:35.730
With all my heart,gentlemen both.

1231
00:58:35.730 --> 00:58:37.100
How fare you?

1232
00:58:37.100 --> 00:58:41.070
Ever at the best, hearingwell of Your Lordship.

1233
00:58:41.070 --> 00:58:42.670
The swallow follows notsummer

1234
00:58:42.670 --> 00:58:45.200
more willing than we, YourLordship.

1235
00:58:45.200 --> 00:58:47.400
Nor more willingly leaveswinter;

1236
00:58:47.400 --> 00:58:48.830
such summer-birds are men.

1237
00:58:55.270 --> 00:58:58.900
Our dinner will notrecompense this long stay.

1238
00:59:01.530 --> 00:59:03.670
Feast your ears with themusic awhile,

1239
00:59:03.670 --> 00:59:07.930
if they will fare so harshlyof the trumpet's sound;

1240
00:59:07.930 --> 00:59:10.470
we will to it presently.

1241
00:59:22.900 --> 00:59:27.800
I hope it remains notunkindly with Your Lordship

1242
00:59:27.800 --> 00:59:29.630
that I returned you anempty messenger.

1243
00:59:29.630 --> 00:59:31.300
O, sir, let it not troubleyou.

1244
00:59:38.230 --> 00:59:39.370
My noble lord

1245
00:59:39.370 --> 00:59:41.200
My good friend, whatcheer?

1246
00:59:41.200 --> 00:59:45.070
My most honorable lord, Iam even sick of shame that,

1247
00:59:45.070 --> 00:59:47.070
when this other day YourLordship sent to me,

1248
00:59:47.070 --> 00:59:49.230
I was so unfortunate abeggar.

1249
00:59:49.230 --> 00:59:50.670
Think not on it.

1250
00:59:50.670 --> 00:59:53.300
If you had sent but twohours before

1251
00:59:53.300 --> 00:59:55.500
Let it not cumber yourbetter remembrance.

1252
01:00:03.170 --> 01:00:04.400
Come, bring in alltogether.

1253
01:00:08.330 --> 01:00:09.730
All covered dishes.

1254
01:00:09.730 --> 01:00:11.330
Royal cheer, I warrantyou.

1255
01:00:11.330 --> 01:00:12.600
I doubt not that,

1256
01:00:12.600 --> 01:00:15.000
if money and the seasoncan yield it.

1257
01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:16.000
How do you?

1258
01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:17.100
What's the news?

1259
01:00:17.100 --> 01:00:19.170
Alcibiades is banished.

1260
01:00:19.170 --> 01:00:20.300
Hear you of it?

1261
01:00:20.300 --> 01:00:22.070
Alcibiades banished.

1262
01:00:22.070 --> 01:00:23.630
'Tis so; be sure of it.

1263
01:00:23.630 --> 01:00:24.630
How, how?

1264
01:00:24.630 --> 01:00:26.330
I pray you, upon what?

1265
01:00:26.330 --> 01:00:28.070
My worthy friends, willyou draw near?

1266
01:00:28.070 --> 01:00:29.330
I'll tell you more anon.

1267
01:00:29.330 --> 01:00:31.070
Here's a noble feasttoward.

1268
01:00:31.070 --> 01:00:33.300
This is the old man still.

1269
01:00:33.300 --> 01:00:34.400
Will it do? Will it do?

1270
01:00:34.400 --> 01:00:35.400
It does.

1271
01:00:35.400 --> 01:00:37.000
But time will, and so

1272
01:00:37.000 --> 01:00:38.400
I do conceive.

1273
01:00:45.070 --> 01:00:48.000
Each man to his stool,with that spur as he would

1274
01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:50.000
to the lip of hismistress.

1275
01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:52.030
Your diet shall be in allplaces alike.

1276
01:00:52.030 --> 01:00:54.900
Make not a city feast ofit, to let the meat cool

1277
01:00:54.900 --> 01:00:56.700
ere we can agree upon thefirst place.

1278
01:00:56.700 --> 01:00:58.530
Sit, sit.

1279
01:01:02.670 --> 01:01:04.070
The gods require ourthanks.

1280
01:01:09.470 --> 01:01:12.070
You great benefactors,

1281
01:01:12.070 --> 01:01:16.730
sprinkle our society withthankfulness.

1282
01:01:16.730 --> 01:01:21.270
For your own gifts, letyourselves be praised.

1283
01:01:21.270 --> 01:01:26.270
But reserve still to give,lest your deities be despised.

1284
01:01:26.270 --> 01:01:29.100
Lend to each man enough,

1285
01:01:29.100 --> 01:01:31.970
that one need not lend toanother;

1286
01:01:31.970 --> 01:01:34.030
for, were your godheads toborrow of men,

1287
01:01:34.030 --> 01:01:37.000
men would forsake thegods.

1288
01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:38.270
Let the meat be beloved

1289
01:01:38.270 --> 01:01:41.370
more than the man thatgives it.

1290
01:01:41.370 --> 01:01:45.030
Let no assembly of twenty bewithout a score of villains.

1291
01:01:45.030 --> 01:01:48.100
if there sit twelve womenat the table,

1292
01:01:48.100 --> 01:01:50.200
let a dozen of them be asthey are.

1293
01:01:52.770 --> 01:01:56.130
The rest of your fees, yougods

1294
01:01:56.130 --> 01:01:57.300
the senators of Athens,

1295
01:01:57.300 --> 01:01:58.830
together with the commonlag of people

1296
01:01:58.830 --> 01:02:00.370
what is amiss in them,

1297
01:02:00.370 --> 01:02:04.770
you gods, make suitablefor destruction.

1298
01:02:04.770 --> 01:02:09.100
For these, my present friends,as they are nothing to me,

1299
01:02:09.100 --> 01:02:10.530
so in nothing bless them,

1300
01:02:10.530 --> 01:02:13.170
and to nothing are theywelcome.

1301
01:02:20.530 --> 01:02:22.930
Uncover, dogs, and lap.

1302
01:02:32.300 --> 01:02:34.370
What does His Lordshipmean?

1303
01:02:34.370 --> 01:02:36.230
I know not.

1304
01:02:36.230 --> 01:02:37.900
May you a better feastnever behold,

1305
01:02:37.900 --> 01:02:40.900
you knot of mouth-friends.

1306
01:02:40.900 --> 01:02:45.130
Smoke and lukewarm wateris your perfection.

1307
01:02:45.130 --> 01:02:46.530
This is Timon's last;

1308
01:02:46.530 --> 01:02:49.930
who, stuck and spangledwith your flatteries,

1309
01:02:49.930 --> 01:02:53.400
washes it off, andsprinkles in your faces

1310
01:02:53.400 --> 01:02:59.100
your reeking villainy.

1311
01:02:59.100 --> 01:03:00.430
Live loathed and long,

1312
01:03:00.430 --> 01:03:06.370
most smiling, smooth,detested parasites,

1313
01:03:06.370 --> 01:03:13.370
courteous destroyers,affable wolves, meek bears,

1314
